# Auto Git Commit After Changes

## CRITICAL — this is non-negotiable

Committing after every file change is **not optional**. It is the last step of every task, without exception.

**Do not wait for the user to ask. Do not batch commits across tasks. Do not finish a response without committing if files were changed.**

If you wrote or modified files and did not commit them, you have not finished the task.

---

## When to commit

- Immediately after completing any set of file writes or edits
- One commit per logical task — if a task touches multiple files, stage and commit them together
- Before responding to the next user message

## Commit title

Use the Conventional Commits format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>
```

Common types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `chore`, `test`, `style`, `ci`

## Commit body

- Explain **what** was changed (which files and what was modified in them)
- Explain **why** by referencing the user's prompt(s) that drove the change — summarise the intent behind the request, not just the literal words

## Hard rules

- Stage only the files changed in this task — never `git add -A` or `git add .`
- Always write the commit message via a heredoc to preserve formatting
- Never skip hooks (`--no-verify`)
- Never amend existing commits — always create a new commit
